# A spatio-temporal land use/land cover reconstruction for India (1960-2010)

This data repository contains annual land use/land cover maps for India between
1960-2010, as well as the input data and code required to generate the maps. A
A Data Descriptor article describing the dataset is currently under review in
Scientific Data. In the following sections we describe the purpose of the various
subdirectories and explain how to reproduce the results.



## maps/

This directory contains land use/land cover maps for India between
1960-2010 at 100m x 100m resolution, in Lambert Conformal Conic
projection. The maps were created by combining a contemporary
land use/land cover map (2005) with district-level inventory data
(1960-2010).



## code/

This directory contains the various scripts used to produce the land use/land
cover dataset. They should be run in the following order:

1.  grass_process_sample_data.sh

    This script processes the spatial input data (in data-raw/) to ensure the
    various maps have the same extent and resolution.

2.  grass_zonal_statistics.sh

    This script adds category information to the three observed land use/land
    cover datasets for 1985, 1995 and 2005 and calculates the quantity of each
    category in each district using the GRASS module r.stats.

3.  grass_sample_data.sh

    This script randomly selects 1000 pixels per category (i.e. 9000 pixels in
    total) which are subsequently used to train and test the random forest
    models.

4.  fit_pred_models.R

    This script fits random forest predictive models for cropland, forest,
    grassland, shrubland, wasteland, urban classes, using the points sampled in
    grass_sample_data.sh. 

5.  write_suit_maps.R

    This script uses the random forest models obtained in fit_pred_models.R to
    predict the suitability of each pixel in the study region to the various land
    use/land cover types, and writes this information to file one district at a
    time (this is necessary because R does not efficiently handle very large
    raster files). 

6.  grass_mosaic_suit_maps.sh

    This script mosaics the district suitability maps into a single suitability
    surface for each land use/land cover type.

7.  state_data_1880_1980.R

8.  quality_control_data.R

    This script performs all quality control operations on the land use/land
    cover inventory data. It uses a set of functions that are available in
    quality_control_funs.R - principally check_data().

9.  run_allocation.R

    This script runs the HILDA land change model on each district in turn.

10. grass_mosaic_lu_maps.sh

    This script mosaics the simulated district level land use/land cover
    maps into single maps for each year of the study period (i.e. 1960-2010),
    writing the output to maps/.

11. grass_process_output.sh

    This script reads the observed (i.e. remote sensing-based) and simulated land
    use/land cover maps for 2005 and 1985 into GRASS and then aggregates them to
    a resolution of 16 times the native resolution of 100m x 100m. The aggregated
    maps show the fraction of the coarse grid cell that belongs to each land use
    type (thus there are 9 maps for each year, representing the various land
    use/land cover types). This information is used to construct Figure 6
    (Components of agreement and disagreement) in the Scientific Data paper. 

12. make_plots.R

    This script produces the plots in the accompanying Scientific Data paper. By
    default the plots will be written to the project directory - change the
    'outdir' variable to place them somewhere else.

Shell scripts (*.sh) utilise a combination of command line programs (e.g. GDAL
tools) and GRASS GIS modules. It assumes you have an installation of GRASS GIS
(>=7.2.2) on your computer, with the GISDBASE parameter set to
'$HOME/grassdata'. No other information is required because the first script
(grass_process_spatial_data.sh) will automatically create the required GRASS
locations on your computer if they do not already exist. We utilise the GRASS
addon 'r.sample.category', which can be installed from within GRASS using the
g.extension module (https://grass.osgeo.org/grass72/manuals/g.extension.html)

In each script, you will need to set the working directory variable ('wd') to the
location of the project directory (e.g. '$HOME/india_lulcc_1960-2010'). They
should be run from the command line, e.g.

```
code/grass_process_spatial_data.sh
```

R scripts rely on a number of packages (see the library() commands at the top of
each script) which must be installed on your system. Run the scripts from the R
(>=3.4.1) command prompt, e.g.

```
source("code/fit_pred_models.R")
```



## data-raw/

This directory contains the spatial input data. Note that we are not allowed to
redistribute the Bioclim data, so you must download this yourself, either
directly from the website (http://worldclim.org/version2) or with the
download_bioclim.sh script included in data-raw (which contains a wget
instruction to retrieve the data from the website).



## data/

This directory, initially empty, is used to contain intermediate and final output
data.



## pkg/

This directory contains two R packages used in the processing workflow. The first,
indagridat, is a data package containing the district-level land use/land cover
inventory data, while lulcc is an R package for land use change modelling
containing the implementation of HILDA as well as functions for model validation.
Development versions of these packages are available from my github page
(https://github.com/simonmoulds).



